	   <a name=96775622327856></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96775622327856><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>Weight Management</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=726><span id=Scholar>SykeAuttic</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>34 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 31st 5:10 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>With our need to stay below 14 weight we need some simple solutions to be able to carry loot, make money, and eventually acquire weightless items.<br><br>One solution:&nbsp;&nbsp;If you are several zones (ie more than 3) away or it will take 20 minutes to run to town consider trading your cash for lightweight gems.  Gems are nice as they stack, are light, and hold their value fairly well around the zones.  Jewelry and other light items like words, runes, etc can also be used, but they will tend to fill up your inventory very fast.  The only disadvantage here is that you may lose a few gold to a few plat by buying one play and selling to a merchant somewhere else.  I used to buy jade with my human monk.  They cost him approx 3p and I could sell them to another merchant for around 2.5p.  I lost .5p for each one, but I was able to reduce my run time to a bank so I was able to collect more cash between trips which more than made up for "loss".<br><br>Another option is to buy and sell back to the vendor.  When you have a ton of gold, silver, or copper you can buy the items you need like food, water, bandages, throwing knives, etc...  but with the left over cash, you can also buy and resell back to that same merchant.  just pick something that costs just shy of 2 plat (like 1p 8g) and in most cases, you can sell that very item back to the same merchant for just over a plat.  Again, you lose a little in the process, but its better than burning copper and silver.<br><br>Of course you can also utilize a banker, if one is in zone, have one of your party members hold the cash for you, or just rely on master looting and get your share at the end of the session.  <br><br>Using the first 2 methods, I was able to keep my human monk in SK for 4-5 levels at a time without going to a city to bank, and later during the Ogguk invasion (LOL) I was able to do the same...<br><br>It was nice because I went from my first 1kp during my time in SK, to over 15kp during my time in Ogguk.    <br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
